SIMPLE: forge
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Forge
<hw>Forge</hw> <pr>(f⟦omac⟧rj)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>forge</ets>, fr. L. <ets>fabrica</ets> the workshop of an artisan
who works in hard materials, fr. <ets>faber</ets> artisan, smith, as
adj., skillful, ingenious; cf. Gr. <?/ soft, tender. Cf.
<er>Fabric</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A place or establishment where
iron or other metals are wrought by heating and hammering; especially, a
furnace, or a shop with its furnace, etc., where iron is heated and
wrought; a smithy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the quick <qex>forge</qex> and working house of thought.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The works where wrought iron is produced directly
from the ore, or where iron is rendered malleable by puddling and
shingling; a shingling mill.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The act of beating or working iron or steel; the
manufacture of metallic bodies.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the greater bodies the <qex>forge</qex> was easy.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>American forge</b></col>, <cd>a forge for the direct
production of wrought iron, differing from the old Catalan forge mainly
in using finely crushed ore and working continuously.</cd>
<au>Raymond.</au> -- <col><b>Catalan forge</b></col>.
<fld>(Metal.)</fld> <cd>See under <er>Catalan</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Forge cinder</b></col>, <cd>the dross or slag form a forge or
bloomary.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Forge rolls</b></col>, <col><b>Forge
train</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the train of rolls by which a bloom is
converted into puddle bars.</cd> -- <col><b>Forge wagon</b></col>
<fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>a wagon fitted up for transporting a blackmith's
forge and tools.</cd> -- <col><b>Portable forge</b></col>, <cd>a light
and compact blacksmith's forge, with bellows, etc., that may be moved
from place to place.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Forge
<hw>Forge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Forged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Forging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>forger</ets>, OF. <ets>forgier</ets>, fr. L. <ets>fabricare</ets>,
<ets>fabricari</ets>, to form, frame, fashion, from <ets>fabrica</ets>.
See <er>Forge</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf. <er>Fabricate</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To form by heating and hammering; to beat into any
particular shape, as a metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Mars's armor <qex>forged</qex> for proof eterne.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form or shape out in any way; to produce; to
frame; to invent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those names that the schools <qex>forged</qex>, and put into the
mouth of scholars, could never get admittance into common use.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Do <qex>forge</qex> a life-long trouble for ourselves.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To coin.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make falsely; to produce, as that which is untrue
or not genuine; to fabricate; to counterfeit, as, a signature, or a
signed document.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That paltry story is untrue,⟦br⟧
And <qex>forged</qex> to cheat such gulls as you.</q>
<rj><qau>Hudibras.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Forged</qex> certificates of his . . . moral character.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To fabricate; counterfeit; feign;
falsify.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Forge
<hw>Forge</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Forge</er>, <pos>v.
t.</pos>, and for sense 2, cf. <er>Forge</er> compel.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To commit forgery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To move heavily and slowly, as a
ship after the sails are furled; to work one's way, as one ship in
outsailing another; -- used especially in the phrase <xex>to forge
ahead</xex>.</def> <rj><au>Totten.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And off she [a ship] <qex>forged</qex> without a shock.</q>
<rj><qau>De Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forge</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Forge
<hw>Forge</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To impel
forward slowly; <as>as, to <ex>forge</ex> a ship forward</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>forged</ent>⟦br⟧
